---
description: Read the full Greenlight skill before any Greenlight work — even if the Greenlight MCP server is unavailable — and re-read it after context compaction.
alwaysApply: true
---

When you do anything involving Greenlight — building, changing, deploying, verifying, debugging, or
maintaining a Greenlight-governed app, or working in any repo with a `greenlight.yml` — read the
**entire** Greenlight skill (`skills/greenlight/SKILL.md`) from start to finish before you act.
Don't act on a partial read or a remembered summary.

**An unavailable MCP connection is not a reason to skip the skill or stop.** If the Greenlight MCP
server is missing from your tool list, disconnected, or failing auth, read the skill anyway: it
explains the bundled `greenlight` CLI, which authenticates independently of MCP and can do
everything the MCP tools can. Never tell the user "Greenlight isn't working" without having read
the skill and tried the CLI path it describes.

The skill defines the load-bearing order of operations (register → clone with the `getRepoAccess`
token → declare infra in `greenlight.yml` → open the PR → wait for the pipeline → merge → verify
and show the app with `getAppPreviewUrl`) and which MCP tools to use for what (`listApps`,
`listGrantableIntegrations`, `getRepoAccess`, `getApp`, `getPipelineRun`, `getAppPreviewUrl`, …),
each with a CLI equivalent. Skipping it leads to wrong tool usage and wrong sequencing.

If your context was summarized or compacted, re-read the entire skill before continuing Greenlight
work. Subagents must read it too — never hand Greenlight work to a subagent that has not read the
full skill.
